<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-11-27T16:13:11-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-11-27T16:13:11-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7198&amp;p=70600#p70600</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7198&amp;p=70600#p70600"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NTSC vs PAL vs HDTV]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7198&amp;p=70600#p70600"><![CDATA[
Fsc is defined as 39.3750/11 MHz, so 3.75*Fsc is 13.4233 MHz, just a hair slow. F<span style="font-size: 84%; line-height: normal">601</span> = 13.5000 MHz was chosen because it is exactly 858 times the scanline frequency on NTSC (Fsc/227.5) and exactly 864 times the scanline frequency on PAL (15625 Hz). The exact ratio is F<span style="font-size: 84%; line-height: normal">601</span> = 132/35 * Fsc = 3.7714 * Fsc.<br /><br />Rec. 601 also defines a frequency for square pixel sampling on NTSC. This is 24/7 * Fsc (12.2727 MHz) for 640x480i SDTV, or 12/7 * Fsc (6.13636 MHz) for 320x240p LDTV. So Genesis pixels (15/8 * Fsc = 6.71165 MHz) are narrow, and Neo Geo pixels (6.00000 MHz) are a hair wide.<br /><br />Of course, the other way to do this is to sample at 4 * Fsc. This is, for example, the dot clock rate for Apple II video.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sat Nov 27, 2010 4:13 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
