<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">psycopathicteen wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">2) How many pixels do HDTV's sample from an NTSC (or PAL) signal per line.<br /></div><br />The standard (Rec. 601) is 720 samples at 13.5 MHz, of which 704 are picture (such that 704x480 covers 4:3) and 16 are "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nominal_analogue_blanking" class="postlink">nominal analog blanking</a>", which is outside even the overscan area. These 704 samples cover 280 pixels of the NES or Super NES video signal.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I think the best NTSC to HDTV conversion would have to sample the NTSC signal at a multiple of 170, possible 3x or 4x.<br /></div><br />Apparently, the standard is to demodulate the chroma, which converts the composite video to component video, in the analog domain before sampling.</div><br /><br />Would that be 3.75x colorburst?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4383">psycopathicteen</a> — Sat Nov 27, 2010 2:15 pm</p><hr />
